SIMPLE: liquidate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Liquidate
<hw>Liq"ui*date</hw> <pr>(l⟦icr⟧k"w⟦icr⟧*d⟦amac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v.
t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Liquidated</conjf>
<pr>(-d⟦amac⟧`t⟦ecr⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Liquidating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[LL. <ets>liquidatus</ets>,
p. p. of <ets>liquidare</ets> to liquidate, fr. L. <ets>liquidus</ets>
liquid, clear. See <er>Liquid</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld>
<def>To determine by agreement or by litigation the precise amount of
(indebtedness); or, where there is an indebtedness to more than one
person, to determine the precise amount of (each indebtedness); to make
the amount of (an indebtedness) clear and certain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A debt or demand is <qex>liquidated</qex> whenever the amount due
is agreed on by the parties, or fixed by the operation of law.</q>
<rj><qau>15 Ga. Rep. 321.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If our epistolary accounts were fairly <qex>liquidated</qex>, I
believe you would be brought in considerable debtor.</q>
<rj><qau>Chesterfield.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In an extended sense: To ascertain the amount, or
the several amounts, of, and apply assets toward the discharge of (an
indebtedness).</def> <rj><au>Abbott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To discharge; to pay off or settle, as an
indebtedness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Friburg was ceded to Zurich by Sigismund to <qex>liquidate</qex> a
debt of a thousand florins.</q> <rj><qau>W. Coxe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make clear and intelligible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Time only can <qex>liquidate</qex> the meaning of all parts of a
compound system.</q> <rj><qau>A. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To make liquid.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To convert (assets) into cash.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To kill; -- used mostly of governments or
organizations killing their enemies; <as>as, Stalin <ex>liquidated</ex>
many of the Kulaks</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To dissolve (an organization); to terminate (an
activity).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Liquidated damages</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>,
<cd>damages the amount of which is fixed or ascertained.</cd>
<rj><au>Abbott.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Liquidation</ent>⟦br⟧
